\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Hello again. Last time we showed how plotting time series data with points joined up by lines helps us see seasonal patterns. We'll now move on to discuss decomposing a seasonal series into component parts. We'll emphasise investigating seasonal differences. We'll start by looking at the visitor arrivals from the US. A basic time series plot with a smoother added, summarising the trend. We're thinking of what we see in terms of an underlying trend with a seasonal pattern superimposed on top of it. There are various ways of getting the trend. This is just a smoother applied to the scatter plot. Well we could smooth the series for each quarter separately and then average the smooths. Here's a seasonal plot for USA.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.futurelearn.com/courses/data-to-insight/8/steps/508418#"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b \cf2 \strokec2 1:06\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Skip to 1 minute and 6 seconds\cb1 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
\cf4 We've seen things like the left hand panel before. We plot against quarter and draw a separate profile for each year. But what about the right hand panel? It's the average seasonal effect. (We'll deal with the annotations later.) So what's the right hand picture and how is it made? It goes basically like this. The first quarter of each year is marked with a blue green line. The last quarter with an orange line. Let's focus on the first year and stretch it out.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.futurelearn.com/courses/data-to-insight/8/steps/508418#"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b \cf2 \strokec2 1:38\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Skip to 1 minute and 38 seconds\cb1 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
\cf4 We'll put the actual points back on and take away the lines. Put on the distances the points are from the trend. Put it on a level playing field so that the distances are all we're seeing. Put the lines back on. And store it away in the right hand window. Now do this for every year. Take the average at each quarter. Connect it up. That's your average seasonal effect. But don't worry, you'll never have to actually do any of this. Software does it for you. We simply showed it to you to help you understand what the red line represents.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.futurelearn.com/courses/data-to-insight/8/steps/508418#"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b \cf2 \strokec2 2:19\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Skip to 2 minutes and 19 seconds\cb1 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
\cf4 So if we think the seasonal effects are fairly constant over time, it makes sense to use this and think that generally, the January to March figures will be 21,000 visitors above what you'd expect from the trend. The April to June figures are about 13,000 below. July to September is about 17,000 below. And October to December is about 8,000 above what you'd expect from the trend. Often the trend is fairly flat over a single year, so that we could think of these as deviations from the yearly average. We can also look at differences between quarters in the obvious way.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.futurelearn.com/courses/data-to-insight/8/steps/508418#"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b \cf2 \strokec2 2:59\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Skip to 2 minutes and 59 seconds\cb1 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
\cf4 For example, we expect the January to March quarter to have about 21 plus 13, which equals 34,000 more visitors from the US than the April to June quarter. Finally, note the horizontal line on this plot at zero. The seasonal terms are up or down adjustments to be made to the trend. Zero is the no-change value because adding zero makes no change. We'll need this idea later when we contrast additive and multiplicative seasonal effects. This is a decomposition plot from iNZight, assuming constant additive seasonal effects. The top panel has the basic plot repeated. The second panel is capturing the seasonal swings assuming that they're all the same apart from purely random differences.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.futurelearn.com/courses/data-to-insight/8/steps/508418#"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b \cf2 \strokec2 3:49\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Skip to 3 minutes and 49 seconds\cb1 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
\cf4 So the seasonal averages are just repeated over and over again. Why? We're hoping to approximate the series well in terms of simple, stable components that we can project into the future to form forecasts. If constant seasonal swings give us good approximations, that's something which is easy to project forwards. We'll ignore the residuals in the third panel for now. Here we're putting the pieces back together again. We're unwrapping the seasonal swings around the trend.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.futurelearn.com/courses/data-to-insight/8/steps/508418#"}}{\fldrslt 
